text.text: A Guide to Kensal Rise & Kensal Green

Don’t think anyone saw it coming when Vogue voted Kensal Rise’s Chamberlayne Road as Europe’s hippest street back in 2009, but several years on and the face of NW10 continues to change. There’s no denying that the area has been on a steady upwards slope of gentrification, but while we’re not here to get into that debate we definitely thought we’d head down and explore these charming residential ends. On your bike sonny, time to have it large like!
KENSAL RISE
Best for… a quick and healthy munch

tip.text:
This family-run business has been going for over 30 years now and not once has the ethos changed: fresh, fast food that bridges the gap between healthy and delicious. Whether you're after a morning bacon bap at 6am or a hearty super-food salad for lunch then this is your spot if you're kicking about in these parts.

The food is fresh, the ingredients are locally sourced and, most importantly, the dishes are mad tasty. Get stuck into the big piri-piri burrito or sweet potato falafel and wash it down with a "green junky" smoothie (cucumber, spinach, avo & coconut milk) - why not? Expect queues around lunchtime.

text.text: First thing in the morning and craving that bacon bap before you slog it to work? Vicki’s has your back, chill. Open from 6am, this family-run spot is all about filling your belly with delicious foodstuff. These guys don’t see why the tag ‘healthy’ should preclude food from being delicious, so expect packed piri-piri burritos, superfood salads, sweet potato falafel and more - all healthy, all tasty. Get ready to queue if you’re coming on your lunch break though!
Best for… breakfast, lunch & dinner

tip.text:
Pub, cocktail bar, restaurant - you name it, they've nailed it. Parlour seeks to be the number one destination for locals at all times of day: swing by in the morning for the papers and a full breakfast or get down for a candlelit dinner, either way this lot have your back.

The menu here is no joke, and while it might be a little ambiguous to read (don't be surprised if you need to ask staff for clarification), there's plenty to keep you coming back. Fan favourites include the hearty cow pie and the chicken kiev, which is styled like a scotch egg and served on a bed of hash brown. Thirsty? The taps are well lubricated and cocktails are certainly going down.

text.text: Master of all trades, jack of none: The Parlour is killing it round the clock, whether you’re looking to tuck into a fancy and wholesome full English, dive into a cow pie or get decently lubricated on cocktails. The cocktail of the week is a paltry £6 yo, and the garden out back is absolutely the one - covered booths so you can still get your munch on al fresco if it’s drizzling a bit and a tree in the centre that gives it a rustic courtyard vibe.
Best for… finding yourself a second home in the ends

tip.text:
We dare you to not love these guys. Bel and Nev are a ridiculously sweet and charming couple - step in here and receive the treatment you'd be chuffed with upon entering someone's home. Sure, it's a pretty small spot, but that only adds to the cosiness and homeliness of the place - simple breakfasts and big smiles can go a long way.

Everything but the baked goods are cooked in the small kitchen here - homemade spiced, slow-cooked beans with chorizo reflect Nev's Brazilian heritage, while the 3-cheese toastie (mozzarella, emmental, cheddar) with pickled onions will melt any self-respecting heart. The staff are all friends and family, as are the customers: join the club.

text.text: A home away from home around the corner from your home? Sounds homely. If you’re after cosy, living room vibes then step into Bel & Nev’s charming cafe. This lovely married couple are running a real family operation and the limited space only adds to the intimacy. Simple, affordable breakfasts are the order here, served with big smiles and equally big hearts. Come towards the end of business hours and you might catch Gee (the legendary Jamaican barber next door) popping in for his daily cake.
Best for… seeing and being seen

tip.text: It’s near impossible to miss the sight of the glasshouse on the Rise - Minki’s deli has become the symbol of the changing face of the area since it opened, whether locals like it or not. The advantages of this glass structure are obvious: an unparalleled amount of natural light and the best people-watching around; perfect for remote working - especially when that comes with some of their homemade cakes. Just don’t throw stones…

Best for… the greenery

tip.text:
This neighbourhood park has everything you could want, from tennis courts to pitch and putt mini-golf, from playgrounds to urban farms: don't act like that doesn't pique your interest. Once the sun's out you'll pretty much find every local kicking back here in the sun - it's tranquil, open and plenty green. Grab a bite or drink at the cafe but be warned of the prices.

Keep your ear to the ground over summer: Queen's Park Day is a great community event and the Where is Nomad open cinema even pops up here on occasion.

text.text: This is the summer spot so take note: tennis; pitch ‘n’ putt golf; urban farm; bandstand; playground. You know that saying “be all things to all men?” No? Well it’s a thing and Queen’s Park has something for absolutely everyone. The green spaces are ample, the vibe is a friendly, neighbourhood one and Minki’s will be manning the cafe from summer ‘16. Other highlights include Queen’s Park Day and when the Where Is The Nomad open cinema pops up.
KENSAL GREEN
Best for… a bite on the street, Mediterranean style

tip.text:
You'll find plenty of North West natives spilling out on the streets on this stretch of College Road, but it's the ones really in the know that you'll catch sitting outside L'Angolo. A legendary deli in these parts thanks to the owner and neighbourhood Stalwart Carmelo, this is the spot to pick up all of those wonderful, authentic Italian ingredients, from dried pasta to cheeses and meats.

The coffee here is delicious and eye-popping, while the paninis are, as you would expect, top of the range; build it the way you see fit out of your favourite bits and bobs. Enjoy all of this out front and indulge in a healthy dose of people watching, why don't you?

text.text: Carmelo is a legend round these parts - so much so that you’ll have to forgive certain locals for referring to L’Angolo as simply Carmelo’s. It’s easy to see why, too: the finest Italian hams, cheeses and foodstuff, from panetones to dried pasta, can be sourced here. Heck, even groceries. The seating out front is great for watching the world go by with a cup of strong, Italian coffee. Do yourself a favour and get a panini - choose the bread and fillings as you please, it’s hard to go wrong.
Best for... meeting the locals

tip.text:
Tucked away in a little suburban corner of Kensal Rise, this cafe is endearing as hell and the epitome of pleasant. Something of a local legend for its ever-changing range of exotic foods, vibrant salads, and cracking fry-ups, this is an excellent choice for lunch, brunch, or afternoon tea.

They also assert a shared love for both coffee and beer - exactly what we want to hear when choosing a cosy cafe in which to lounge the afternoon away.

text.text: A real neighbourhood (m)eating spot for NW10 natives, it seems as though there's a steady stream of locals popping in and out of Gracelands. Expect an international menu that mirrors the diversity of the area (the jerk chicken is actually mad good), while classes for new mothers out back help families in the community come together. It can be rammed with kids at times, so avoid the after-school rush if you want quiet.
Best for… heavy lifting and beer garden chillin’

tip.text:
Spacious and cosy at the same time, The Masons Arms is a criminally underrated pub around these parts. That said, those who know, know. Drink prices here are pretty reasonable given the times we live in, while you'll be able to catch a range of sporting events on the screens here.

It's the treasure out back that really sets this place apart. The beer garden here is off the chain - enough room and seating for your whole crew and then some, plus BBQs pop off here throughout the summer and are well worth a gander. DJs on weekends make The Masons ideal for a cheeky boogie, while proximity to Notting Hill Carnival doesn't hurt either.
